content: Garbage in - garbage out. This app is just an immitation based on the data from your camera/file. And this input data is garbage. When creating IR files, the app treats all red colored objects as warm and the green colored as cold. The actual IR data is filtered from your camera, so this app cannot guess which parts of the image are warm and which - cold. A picture of my head whith open mouth shows my face warmer than inside my mouth. Similar fot he UV immitation. Still fun.

IT REALLY WORKS! So many frauds in the past, finally a near IR, UV cam, and its genuine, not ridiculous psychedelic color, well, it does some, but you can ignore it. I do. No. This is the real deal . Within its working range, this app serves it well.

replyContent: Sunscreen? It absorbs in the range shorter than 380nm, but the silicon camera works from about 400nm. Obviously, a smartphone camera with polycarbonate optics will worse in UV than a specially designed camera with quartz or mirror optics.

content: Excitement and some terror when I turned lights on my skin.... loved it

to test the infrared sensing capability I turned on one burner on my electric stove. The image was exactly the same as the adjacent burner that was cold. therefore this app is not sensing infrared energy. it appears to be only colorizing the image based on external light
replyContent: According to Wien's displacement law, the stove at 400C has a maximum emission at ~4μm. Si sensors work up to 1.1um, in color sensors the range is limited up to 0.4-0.7 um. At best case, the app works up to ~0.85um, although 0.94um passes into the blue channel (nonideality of the light filter), but is interpreted as ultraviolet.
